    <!-- BaseOnChangeListener<S> / BaseOnSliderTouchListener<S> are Google-internal
         (@RestrictTo(LIBRARY_GROUP) / @hide) generic interfaces that only exist to provide a
         type bound for BaseSlider's generic listener parameters. They must NOT be bound:
         1. They are generic with an unbounded type parameter, so they bind with an erased
            onValueChange(Object, ...) / onStartTrackingTouch(Object) method.
         2. The public typed sub-interfaces (Slider.OnChangeListener, RangeSlider.OnChangeListener,
            and the touch equivalents) extend them and redeclare the method with the concrete type
            (onValueChange(Slider, ...)). A managed class implementing a typed sub-interface then
            inherits BOTH the erased base method and the typed method, and the generated Android
            Callable Wrapper emits two Java methods with the same erasure -> javac "name clash".
         3. Emptying the base interfaces (removing only their methods) is also invalid: the generator
            still emits Android Callable Wrapper implementors for them, but with no __md_methods,
            producing empty Java classes that still 'implements' the abstract Java interfaces ->
            javac "is not abstract and does not override abstract method" (issue #1484).
         Removing the interfaces entirely leaves only the public typed sub-interfaces, whose
         implementors override exactly the concrete method they declare and compile cleanly. -->
    <remove-node
      path="/api/package[@name='com.google.android.material.slider']/interface[@name='BaseOnChangeListener']" />
    <remove-node
      path="/api/package[@name='com.google.android.material.slider']/interface[@name='BaseOnSliderTouchListener']" />

    <!-- The public typed sub-interfaces extend the internal base interfaces removed above. Drop the
         now-dangling <implements> so they bind as standalone interfaces that declare only their own
         concrete method (e.g. onValueChange(Slider, float, boolean)). Their implementors then
         override exactly that method and compile (javac synthesizes the erased bridge). -->
    <remove-node
      path="/api/package[@name='com.google.android.material.slider']/interface[@name='Slider.OnChangeListener']/implements" />
    <remove-node
      path="/api/package[@name='com.google.android.material.slider']/interface[@name='Slider.OnSliderTouchListener']/implements" />
    <remove-node
      path="/api/package[@name='com.google.android.material.slider']/interface[@name='RangeSlider.OnChangeListener']/implements" />
    <remove-node
      path="/api/package[@name='com.google.android.material.slider']/interface[@name='RangeSlider.OnSliderTouchListener']/implements" />

    <!-- With the internal base interfaces removed, type the BaseSlider add/remove listener
         parameters (generic type variables L and T) as java.lang.Object. Slider/RangeSlider expose
         the strongly typed AddOnChangeListener/AddOnSliderTouchListener overloads via Additions; a
         typed listener instance (which IS-A BaseOnChangeListener in Java) is passed straight through
         to these Object-typed methods at runtime. -->
    <attr
